{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-b9043a893f1ea105", "type": "tool_result", "content": "=== 2104.01466 ===\n# ECAPA-TDNN Embeddings for Speaker Diarization\narXiv: 2104.01466\nAuthors: Nauman Dawalatabad, Mirco Ravanelli, François Grondin, Jenthe Thienpondt, Brecht Desplanques, Hwidong Na\nYear: 2021 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_representation\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. The ECAPA-TDNN model is extended to speaker diarization for the first time, providing robust speaker embeddings for short speaker turns.\n  2. A powerful data augmentation scheme is introduced that concatenates multiple contaminated versions of the same signal within the same training batch to improve model robustness.\n  3. The proposed system significantly outperforms recent speaker diarization approaches on the AMI meeting corpus under both close-talking and distant-talking conditions.\n\nTags: ASR\n\n=== 2104.03603 ===\n# AISHELL-4: An Open Source Dataset for Speech Enhancement, Separation, Recognition and Speaker Diarization in Conference Scenario\narXiv: 2104.03603\nAuthors: Yihui Fu, Luyao Cheng, Shubo Lv, Yukai Jv, Yuxiang Kong, Zhuo Chen, Yanxin Hu, Lei Xie, Jian Wu, Hui Bu, Xin Xu, Jun Du, Jingdong Chen\nYear: 2021 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_dataset\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduction of AISHELL-4, a sizable 120-hour real-recorded 8-channel Mandarin speech dataset for conference scenarios featuring natural acoustic characteristics like speech overlap and noise.\n  2. Provision of accurate transcriptions and speaker voice activity annotations to support diverse speech processing tasks ranging from front-end processing to joint optimization.\n  3. Offering the only open-source Mandarin conversation speech dataset to enhance linguistic diversity in the speech research community.\n  4. Release of a PyTorch-based training and evaluation framework as a baseline system to promote reproducible research.\n\nTags: ASR\n\n=== 2203.16844 ===\n# Open Source MagicData-RAMC: A Rich Annotated Mandarin Conversational(RAMC) Speech Dataset\narXiv: 2203.16844\nAuthors: Zehui Yang, Yifan Chen, Lei Luo, Runyan Yang, Lingxuan Ye, Gaofeng Cheng, Ji Xu, Yaohui Jin, Qingqing Zhang, Pengyuan Zhang, Lei Xie, Yonghong Yan\nYear: 2022 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_dataset\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduction of MagicData-RAMC, a 180-hour high-quality rich annotated Mandarin conversational speech dataset recorded over mobile phones at a 16 kHz sampling rate.\n  2. Provision of precise voice activity timestamps, topic labels across 15 diversified domains, and detailed speaker demographic information to support extensive speech research.\n  3. Alleviation of the scarcity of public-available, high-quality Mandarin dialog speech datasets with a corpus specifically designed for realistic multi-turn conversational scenarios.\n  4. Establishment of baseline systems and experimental results for automatic speech recognition, speaker diarization, and keyword search tasks to evaluate the dataset.\n\nTags: ASR\n\n=== 2606.02400 ===\n# SoulX-Transcriber: A Robust End-to-End Framework for Multi-Speaker Speech Transcription\narXiv: 2606.02400\nAuthors: Yuhang Dai, Haopeng Lin, Zhennan Lin, Jiale Qian, Jun Wu, Hanke Xie, Hao Meng, Hanlin Wen, Chuang Ding, Shunshun Yin, Ming Tao, Lei Xie, Xinsheng Wang\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: \nStatus: unread\n\n=== 2110.13900 ===\n# WavLM: Large-Scale Self-Supervised Pre-Training for Full Stack Speech Processing\narXiv: 2110.13900\nAuthors: Sanyuan Chen, Chengyi Wang, Zhengyang Chen, Yu Wu, Shujie Liu, Zhuo Chen, Jinyu Li, Naoyuki Kanda, Takuya Yoshioka, Xiong Xiao, Jian Wu, Long Zhou, Shuo Ren, Yanmin Qian, Yao Qian, Jian Wu, Michael Zeng, Xiangzhan Yu, Furu Wei\nYear: 2021 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_representation\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. WavLM introduces a general pre-trained model for full stack speech processing tasks, moving beyond the focus on specific task groups like ASR in prior self-supervised learning works.\n  2. A masked speech denoising and prediction framework is proposed to jointly learn speech content modeling and denoising, effectively improving performance on non-ASR tasks such as speaker verification, diarization, and separation.\n  3. Gated relative position bias is integrated into the Transformer structure to adaptively adjust relative position biases based on current speech content, enhancing sequence ordering capture and ASR performance.\n  4. The self-supervised speech pre-training data is scaled up to 94k hours from diverse domains, alleviating audiobook data bias and improving model robustness.\n  5. State-of-the-art results are achieved on the SUPERB benchmark and representative benchmarks for speaker verification, speech separation, and speaker diarization, with models and code publicly released.\n\nTags: SSL, ASR, SSL/预测式-离散\n\n=== 2501.15907 ===\n# Emilia: A Large-Scale, Extensive, Multilingual, and Diverse Dataset for Speech Generation\narXiv: 2501.15907\nAuthors: Haorui He, Zengqiang Shang, Chaoren Wang, Xuyuan Li, Yicheng Gu, Hua Hua, Liwei Liu, Chen Yang, Jiaqi Li, Peiyang Shi, Yuancheng Wang, Kai Chen, Pengyuan Zhang, Zhizheng Wu\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_dataset\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduction of Emilia-Pipe, the first open-source preprocessing pipeline designed to efficiently transform in-the-wild multilingual speech data into high-quality training datasets for speech generation.\n  2. Construction of Emilia and Emilia-Large, comprising 101k and 216k hours of diverse, in-the-wild speech across six languages, making them among the largest open-source speech generation datasets.\n  3. Demonstration that models trained on in-the-wild Emilia data produce significantly more spontaneous and human-like speech while maintaining the intelligibility of models trained on traditional audio-book datasets.\n  4. Identification of a data scaling law in speech generation where performance improves with dataset size but exhibits diminishing returns beyond 100k hours.\n  5. Validation of the effectiveness of the Emilia-Large dataset for training robust multilingual and crosslingual speech generation models.\n\nTags: TTS, TTS/功能-多语言, TTS/功能-多说话人", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "6379eb56-72ac-4393-84e1-e3a485be1b01", "uuid": "c97cd5f8-e184-43d1-9afa-3a45f209fb1d", "timestamp": "2026-07-15T14:04:18.258Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "=== 2104.01466 ===\n# ECAPA-TDNN Embeddings for Speaker Diarization\narXiv: 2104.01466\nAuthors: Nauman Dawalatabad, Mirco Ravanelli, François Grondin, Jenthe Thienpondt, Brecht Desplanques, Hwidong Na\nYear: 2021 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_representation\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. The ECAPA-TDNN model is extended to speaker diarization for the first time, providing robust speaker embeddings for short speaker turns.\n  2. A powerful data augmentation scheme is introduced that concatenates multiple contaminated versions of the same signal within the same training batch to improve model robustness.\n  3. The proposed system significantly outperforms recent speaker diarization approaches on the AMI meeting corpus under both close-talking and distant-talking conditions.\n\nTags: ASR\n\n=== 2104.03603 ===\n# AISHELL-4: An Open Source Dataset for Speech Enhancement, Separation, Recognition and Speaker Diarization in Conference Scenario\narXiv: 2104.03603\nAuthors: Yihui Fu, Luyao Cheng, Shubo Lv, Yukai Jv, Yuxiang Kong, Zhuo Chen, Yanxin Hu, Lei Xie, Jian Wu, Hui Bu, Xin Xu, Jun Du, Jingdong Chen\nYear: 2021 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_dataset\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduction of AISHELL-4, a sizable 120-hour real-recorded 8-channel Mandarin speech dataset for conference scenarios featuring natural acoustic characteristics like speech overlap and noise.\n  2. Provision of accurate transcriptions and speaker voice activity annotations to support diverse speech processing tasks ranging from front-end processing to joint optimization.\n  3. Offering the only open-source Mandarin conversation speech dataset to enhance linguistic diversity in the speech research community.\n  4. Release of a PyTorch-based training and evaluation framework as a baseline system to promote reproducible research.\n\nTags: ASR\n\n=== 2203.16844 ===\n# Open Source MagicData-RAMC: A Rich Annotated Mandarin Conversational(RAMC) Speech Dataset\narXiv: 2203.16844\nAuthors: Zehui Yang, Yifan Chen, Lei Luo, Runyan Yang, Lingxuan Ye, Gaofeng Cheng, Ji Xu, Yaohui Jin, Qingqing Zhang, Pengyuan Zhang, Lei Xie, Yonghong Yan\nYear: 2022 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_dataset\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduction of MagicData-RAMC, a 180-hour high-quality rich annotated Mandarin conversational speech dataset recorded over mobile phones at a 16 kHz sampling rate.\n  2. Provision of precise voice activity timestamps, topic labels across 15 diversified domains, and detailed speaker demographic information to support extensive speech research.\n  3. Alleviation of the scarcity of public-available, high-quality Mandarin dialog speech datasets with a corpus specifically designed for realistic multi-turn conversational scenarios.\n  4. Establishment of baseline systems and experimental results for automatic speech recognition, speaker diarization, and keyword search tasks to evaluate the dataset.\n\nTags: ASR\n\n=== 2606.02400 ===\n# SoulX-Transcriber: A Robust End-to-End Framework for Multi-Speaker Speech Transcription\narXiv: 2606.02400\nAuthors: Yuhang Dai, Haopeng Lin, Zhennan Lin, Jiale Qian, Jun Wu, Hanke Xie, Hao Meng, Hanlin Wen, Chuang Ding, Shunshun Yin, Ming Tao, Lei Xie, Xinsheng Wang\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: \nStatus: unread\n\n=== 2110.13900 ===\n# WavLM: Large-Scale Self-Supervised Pre-Training for Full Stack Speech Processing\narXiv: 2110.13900\nAuthors: Sanyuan Chen, Chengyi Wang, Zhengyang Chen, Yu Wu, Shujie Liu, Zhuo Ch